            <!-- Contents -->
            <noteGrp type="workDesc">
               <note type="description">A collection of 21 poems written in the muwashshaḥ style
                     – a specifically Andalusian form of poetry which was common to the Muslims,
                     Jews and Christians of the region.</note>
               <note type="structure"/>
               <note type="contentsNote"/>
            </noteGrp>
            <!-- Stemmatics -->
            <note type="stemmatics">There is only one copy of this text, Shehit Ali 1389
                  (c.777H), which has a note saying it was taken from a copy in the hand of IA.
                  There was also a copy now lost in Yusuf Ağa 5503. A comparison with the
                  muwashshaḥāt in the Bulaq Dīwān reveals that the 21 poems in the ms. are all in
                  the Great Dīwān, although the order in which they are presented is different and
                  there are minor textual variations. It is therefore unclear whether this is an
                  extract from some version of the Dīwān, or an earlier version of a work which was
                  later incorporated into it, so for the time being it is regarded as a stand-alone
                  work.</note>
